VSangeeta Ksheerasagaram featured a vocal recital by R.V. Panduranga Sharma as part of the memorial concert of Uppalapati Ankaiah last week at Thyagaraya Gaana Sabha in Hyderabad. He was accompanied by Pavan Singh on the violin and by Shyam Kumar on the mridangam.Sharma is the disciple of Puranam Purushottama Sastry and later learnt under D.K. Pattammal who passed away recently. Sharma follows his gurus in tradition and did his job sincerely despite having a feeble voice.His traditional approach superceded all the shortcomings and made the concert interesting because of the greatpathantharaset by his gurus.He began with thodi varnam in a steady way and tookMakelara Vicharamuin a good tempo in Ravichandrika with brisk swaram of Thyagaraja.Sudha Dhanyasi was briefed for an alap forSri Partha Saradhiof Deeekshitar which was a noted item of D.K. Pattammal.Kamakshi Swarajhathiof Syama Sastry in Yadukula Khambhoji was rendered with a perfect blend of laya, sahityam and ragabhavam. Here he explained the intricacies of the item.Ranganayakianother rare one in Nayaki was sung carefully.The main attraction of the day was Bhairavi.Here Sharma elaborated the raga with care and did his best to give the complete picture of the ragam.Nee Padamuleanother rare krithi of Patnam Subramanyam Iyer was done justice with an imaginative and simple swaram in it.Thepakkavadyamsdid well with their respective instruments on the day. Sharma concluded his recital with a Bharatheeyar compositionEngal Nattu Kendanaduwith a good feel.On the whole Sharma gave a good concert and dedicated the concert to D.K. Pattammal.
